{"title_page": "Prince Mohammad bin Fahd University", "text_new": "{{Infobox university\n| name = Prince Mohammad bin Fahd University\n| native_name = \u062c\u0627\u0645\u0639\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0645\u064a\u0631 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0628\u0646 \u0641\u0647\u062f\n| image = [[File:Prince_Mohammed_Bin_Fahd_University_seal.jpg|250px]]\n| motto = Creative Minds, Transform The World\n| established = September, 2006\n| type = [[Private school|Private]]\n| endowment = \n| president = Dr. Issa Al- Ansari\n| undergrad = \n| postgrad = \n| city = [[Dhahran]]\n| state = [[Eastern Province, Saudi Arabia|Eastern Province]]\n| country = [[Saudi Arabia]]\n| campus = Dhahran, Saudi Arabia\n| website = [http://www.pmu.edu.sa/ www.pmu.edu.sa]\n| logo = [[File:Prince_Mohammed_Bin_Fahd_University_logo_and_motto.png|250px]]\n| faculty = \n}}\n\n'''Prince Mohammad bin Fahd University''' ([[Arabic]]: \u062c\u0627\u0645\u0639\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0645\u064a\u0631 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0628\u0646 \u0641\u0647\u062f ), abbreviated '''PMU''', is a [[private university]] in [[Dhahran]], [[Saudi Arabia]].  It was founded by Prince [[Muhammad bin Fahd]], former governor of the [[Ash Sharqiyah Province|Eastern Province]].<ref name=rbureau>{{cite news |title=10 Saudi Royals Who Could Become the Next Crown Prince| url= http://riyadhbureau.com/succession/| accessdate=25 February 2013| newspaper=Riyadh Bureau| date=2013| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20121213220018/http://riyadhbureau.com/succession| archivedate= 2012-12-13 }}</ref>\n\nThe University is accredited by the Saudi Ministry of Education and regionally by NCAAA (The National Commission for Academic Accreditation and Assessment) with responsibility for determining standards and procedures for accreditation and quality assurance and accrediting postsecondary institutions and programs within the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia.  The Commission is an independent authority, responsible to the Higher Council of Education.  The Commission's objectives, as specified in its bylaws, include a wide range of functions associated with support for improvements of the quality of postsecondary education in all fields of learning other than defense.\n[http://www.ncaaa.org.sa/en/AboutUs/Pages/Vision.aspx] Internationally, the university is seeking accreditation from various accreditation bodies. Currently, the Electrical Engineering department is accredited by [https://www.abet.org/ ABET (formerly known as Accreditation Board for Engineering and Technology)]. Applications for accreditation of the Civil and Mechanical Engineering departments are submitted to the same accreditation body.<ref>{{cite web| title=Prince Mohammad Bin Fahd University: &rlm; \u062c\u0627\u0645\u0639\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0645\u064a\u0631 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0628\u0646 \u0641\u0647\u062f| url=http://www.4icu.org/reviews/13871.htm| website= &lrm;4International Colleges & Universities: University Web Rankings & Reviews| accessdate=13 May 2016| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160426021730/http://www.4icu.org/reviews/13871.htm| archivedate=2016-04-26| date=2016-04-30}}</ref> The university was inaugurated in April 2006<ref>{{cite web| title=New Saudi varsity in Sept| url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/displayArticle.asp?col=&section=middleeast&xfile=data/middleeast/2006/April/middleeast_April702.xml| website=Khaleej Times Online| accessdate=13 May 2016| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060502024417/http://www.khaleejtimes.com/displayArticle.asp?col=&section=middleeast&xfile=data%2Fmiddleeast%2F2006%2FApril%2Fmiddleeast_April702.xml| archivedate=2006-05-02| quote=The Prince Muhammad bin Fahd University in Al Khobar, which was inaugurated recently by Riyadh Governor Prince Salman, is scheduled to become operational in September.| url-status=dead}}</ref> and was formally opened on 8 October 2008 with bachelor's degrees in 17 academic programs, with some courses taught in [[Arabic language|Arabic]] and many in English. It is composed of three colleges: College of [[Engineering]] - [[Civil engineering|Civil]] and [[Mechanical engineering|Mechanical]], initially for males only, but available also for females since the beginning of 2017, and [[Interior Design]] (for females only); [[College of Business]] (both genders- but in segregated programs with most of the faculty on the male side); and College of [[Information Technology]] (both genders). In March 2008 it started an Executive [[Master of Business Administration|EMBA]] program in conjunction with [[Maastricht School of Management]].<ref>{{cite web|title=MSM present at Opening PMU, Saudi Arabia|url=https://www.msm.nl/msm-present-at-opening-pmu-saudi-arabia/|website=MSM: Maastricht School of Management|accessdate=13 May 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150404105916/http://www.msm.nl/msm-present-at-opening-pmu-saudi-arabia/|archivedate=2015-04-04|date=8 October 2008|quote=Last November, MSM signed an agreement with PMU, in which several joint programs in the area of management are covered. The first intake of the dual degree Executive MBA Program started in March with a group of 15 talented managers from the region.}}</ref> As of 17 March 2012, the affiliation with Maastricht was terminated by Maastricht.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}}\n\nAll university buildings were planned for completion in 2008, and the school planned to have a total enrollment of 5,500 by 2012. The university plant was not complete as of the summer of 2009. All administration buildings are on the men's campus and are generally off-limits to the women\u2014 faculty, staff and students. There is a small library, also segregated; the men's side is twice the size of the women's.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n\nThe design is based on the American model for academic programs and administrative organization, and was developed in conjunction with the non-profit [[Texas International Education Consortium]] which organizes experts from the 32 public universities in [[Texas]].<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.tiec.org/exp_mideast.html/#Saudi| website= Texas International Education Consortium| title= Middle East: Saudi Arabia| accessdate= 2016-05-15| date= 2016 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20151022093425/http://www.tiec.org/exp_mideast.html | archivedate= 2015-10-22 | quote= '''Design of Prince Mohammad bin Fahd University'''.... Start: September 2003  End: June 2007. ...'''Curriculum Review'''.... Start: October 2011  End: June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.pmu.edu.sa/}}\n\n{{coord missing|Saudi Arabia}}\n\n{{Portal|Saudi Arabia}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Prince Mohammad Bin Fahd University}}\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:Private universities and colleges in Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:2006 establishments in Saudi Arabia]]\n\n\n{{SaudiArabia-university-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox university\n| name = Prince Mohammad bin Fahd University\n| native_name = \u062c\u0627\u0645\u0639\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0645\u064a\u0631 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0628\u0646 \u0641\u0647\u062f\n| image = [[File:Prince_Mohammed_Bin_Fahd_University_seal.jpg|250px]]\n| motto = Creative Minds, Transform The World\n| established = September, 2006\n| type = [[Private school|Private]]\n| endowment = \n| president = Dr. Issa Al- Ansari\n| undergrad = \n| postgrad = \n| city = [[Dhahran]]\n| state = [[Eastern Province, Saudi Arabia|Eastern Province]]\n| country = [[Saudi Arabia]]\n| campus = Dhahran, Saudi Arabia\n| website = [http://www.pmu.edu.sa/ www.pmu.edu.sa]\n| logo = [[File:Prince_Mohammed_Bin_Fahd_University_logo_and_motto.png|250px]]\n| faculty = \n}}\n\n'''Prince Mohammad bin Fahd University''' ([[Arabic]]: \u062c\u0627\u0645\u0639\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0645\u064a\u0631 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0628\u0646 \u0641\u0647\u062f ), abbreviated '''PMU''', is a [[private university]] in [[Dhahran]], [[Saudi Arabia]].  It was founded by Prince [[Muhammad bin Fahd]], former governor of the [[Ash Sharqiyah Province|Eastern Province]].<ref name=rbureau>{{cite news |title=10 Saudi Royals Who Could Become the Next Crown Prince| url= http://riyadhbureau.com/succession/| accessdate=25 February 2013| newspaper=Riyadh Bureau| date=2013| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20121213220018/http://riyadhbureau.com/succession| archivedate= 2012-12-13 }}</ref>\n\nThe University is accredited by the Saudi Ministry of Education and regionally by NCAAA (The National Commission for Academic Accreditation and Assessment) with responsibility for determining standards and procedures for accreditation and quality assurance and accrediting postsecondary institutions and programs within the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia.  The Commission is an independent authority, responsible to the Higher Council of Education.  The Commission's objectives, as specified in its bylaws, include a wide range of functions associated with support for improvements of the quality of postsecondary education in all fields of learning other than defense.\n[http://www.ncaaa.org.sa/en/AboutUs/Pages/Vision.aspx] Internationally, the university is seeking accreditation from various accreditation bodies. Currently, the Electrical Engineering department is accredited by [https://www.abet.org/ ABET (formerly known as Accreditation Board for Engineering and Technology)]. Applications for accreditation of the Civil and Mechanical Engineering departments are submitted to the same accreditation body.<ref>{{cite web| title=Prince Mohammad Bin Fahd University: &rlm; \u062c\u0627\u0645\u0639\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0645\u064a\u0631 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0628\u0646 \u0641\u0647\u062f| url=http://www.4icu.org/reviews/13871.htm| website= &lrm;4International Colleges & Universities: University Web Rankings & Reviews| accessdate=13 May 2016| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160426021730/http://www.4icu.org/reviews/13871.htm| archivedate=2016-04-26| date=2016-04-30}}</ref> The university was inaugurated in April 2006<ref>{{cite web| title=New Saudi varsity in Sept| url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/displayArticle.asp?col=&section=middleeast&xfile=data/middleeast/2006/April/middleeast_April702.xml| website=Khaleej Times Online| accessdate=13 May 2016| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060502024417/http://www.khaleejtimes.com/displayArticle.asp?col=&section=middleeast&xfile=data%2Fmiddleeast%2F2006%2FApril%2Fmiddleeast_April702.xml| archivedate=2006-05-02| quote=The Prince Muhammad bin Fahd University in Al Khobar, which was inaugurated recently by Riyadh Governor Prince Salman, is scheduled to become operational in September.| url-status=dead}}</ref> and was formally opened on 8 October 2008 with bachelor's degrees in 17 academic programs, with some courses taught in [[Arabic language|Arabic]] and many in English. It is composed of three colleges: College of [[Engineering]] - [[Civil engineering |Civil]] and [[Mechanical engineering |Mechanical]], initially for males only, but available also for females since the beginning of 2017, and [[Interior Design]] (for females only); [[College of Business]] (both genders- but in segregated programs with most of the faculty on the male side); and College of [[Information Technology]] (both genders). In March 2008 it started an Executive [[Master of Business Administration|EMBA]] program in conjunction with [[Maastricht School of Management]].<ref>{{cite web|title=MSM present at Opening PMU, Saudi Arabia|url=https://www.msm.nl/msm-present-at-opening-pmu-saudi-arabia/|website=MSM: Maastricht School of Management|accessdate=13 May 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150404105916/http://www.msm.nl/msm-present-at-opening-pmu-saudi-arabia/|archivedate=2015-04-04|date=8 October 2008|quote=Last November, MSM signed an agreement with PMU, in which several joint programs in the area of management are covered. The first intake of the dual degree Executive MBA Program started in March with a group of 15 talented managers from the region.}}</ref> As of 17 March 2012, the affiliation with Maastricht was terminated by Maastricht.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}}\n\nAll university buildings were planned for completion in 2008, and the school planned to have a total enrollment of 5,500 by 2012. The university plant was not complete as of the summer of 2009. All administration buildings are on the men's campus and are generally off-limits to the women\u2014 faculty, staff and students. There is a small library, also segregated; the men's side is twice the size of the women's.{{cn|date=May 2016}}\n\nThe design is based on the American model for academic programs and administrative organization, and was developed in conjunction with the non-profit [[Texas International Education Consortium]] which organizes experts from the 32 public universities in [[Texas]].<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.tiec.org/exp_mideast.html/#Saudi| website= Texas International Education Consortium| title= Middle East: Saudi Arabia| accessdate= 2016-05-15| date= 2016 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20151022093425/http://www.tiec.org/exp_mideast.html | archivedate= 2015-10-22 | quote= '''Design of Prince Mohammad bin Fahd University'''.... Start: September 2003  End: June 2007. ...'''Curriculum Review'''.... Start: October 2011  End: June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.pmu.edu.sa/}}\n\n{{coord missing|Saudi Arabia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Prince Mohammad Bin Fahd University}}\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:Private universities and colleges in Saudi Arabia]]\n\n\n{{SaudiArabia-university-stub}}{{Portal|Saudi Arabia}}\n[[Category:2006 establishments in Saudi Arabia]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prince_Mohammad_bin_Fahd_University"}
